        <dcterms:abstract>This case study research explores how cybersecurity skills can be a driver for economic growth
in developing countries. The research helps to understand the current issues prohibiting the
development of cybersecurity education, training, and certification programs and challenges,
such as cybercrime impacting critical infrastructure protection in Guyana. This paper seeks
explicitly to a) identify the current state of cybersecurity knowledge, skills, and abilities, b)
identify the existing cybersecurity challenges, and c) examine how cyber-crime impacts the
country. As a known national imperative, the ability to combat cyber-crime and strengthen cyber
resilience is essential to improving national economic and social development. The existing risk
management frameworks echo economic security as a foundational pillar for domestic growth.
The developed nations, specifically the United States, Britain, and Canada, recognize the
importance of critical infrastructure systems. These countries develop strategies that include
cybersecurity education as a measure to protect this infrastructure continuously. Their strategies
are holistic and address elements such as the need for requisite workforce skills to advance
cybersecurity governance programs. The programs support national security objectives but not
without challenges. In contrast, the parallel is not the same for developing nations. These
countries lack the resources to contemplate such strategies and the workforce to protect critical
digital infrastructure</dcterms:abstract>
