        <dc:title>The tourism sector's vulnerability to climate change-related phenomena. Case study: Romania</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>The attractiveness of an area for tourist activities depends significantly on the local weather and climate. Thus, the tourism industry is considered highly vulnerable to climate change. This study relies on the statistical data available at the lowest level of administrative territorial units (LAU or NUTS5) provided by the National Institute of Statistics, and on the climatic data provided by the National Meteorological Administration. The paper aims to develop a multi-criteria vulnerability assessment selecting and processing 25 indicators and identifying the levels of tourism vulnerability to climate change. The indicators have been categorised into the three primary components of vulnerability (Exposure, Sensitivity and Adaptive Capacity). This study aims to achieve several objectives: analysing the main independent variables that lead to tourism activity and are related to climate change, and identifying their spatial pattern; spotting the touristic areas most and least sensitive to climate change; finding the touristic NUTS5/LAUs that are the most and least vulnerable to climate change, while also tracking their adaptive capacity; assessing tourism vulnerability during both summer and winter; characterizing the touristic areas vulnerable to climate change. In this context, the current research holds value for academics by enhancing the general understanding of climate change-related vulnerability in Romania's tourism sector. Additionally, it is beneficial for local decision-makers and planners contributing to the formulation of local climate change-related mitigation and adaptation strategies in the tourism sector. As the first approach dealing with the tourism vulnerability assessment at Romania's lowest administrative level, this study could enhance the representation of the tourism sector in future comprehensive national vulnerability indices.</dcterms:abstract>
