        <dc:title>Assessing levels of safety integrity in tap water quality – A case study approach</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>Maintaining the safety and quality of tap water remains a challenge for the modern water supply systems. In this paper an approach is introduced that uses Levels of Safety Integrity (LSI), a concept mainly employed in industrial and information safety to evaluate and improve tap water safety. The methodology covers the analysis of water consumers through risk assessments, with a specific emphasis on the priority groups, which is a new approach to risk analysis.The proposed methodology entails a systematic risk assessment, hazard identification, and protective measures taken within a probability, consequences, and vulnerability factors based structured framework. The model was applied to real-world data, revealing that microbiological contamination (Clostridium perfringens) posed a high risk, classified as unacceptable (3-LSI) for sensitive consumers, necessitating immediate intervention. In contrast, flood induced turbidity was categorized as controlled (2-LSI) for individual consumers and therefore requires continuous monitoring and mitigation strategies. The case studies presented in this paper show that the research methodology proposed here can be useful for other water supply systems in other regions of the world.</dcterms:abstract>
