        <dc:title>An emergy-based indicator framework for assessing regional ecosystem health and ecological service value: impacts of water conservancy projects</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>Water conservancy projects, vital global infrastructure, profoundly impact the ecosystems of the regions they serve. Assessing their sustainability and the efficacy of resultant ecological services presents a key environmental management challenge, as traditional methods struggle to integrate diverse natural and socioeconomic inputs or unify value within complex human-natural systems. This study introduces an innovative Emergy-based indicator framework, utilizing solar emergy joules (sej) as a unified metric to comprehensively evaluate project impacts and the sustainability of the entire host region. The framework incorporates: (1) a coupled structure–function-efficiency emergy flow network model to trace water conservancy projects impacts across the regional landscape; (2) a multi-dimensional method for valuing ecological services in emergy terms; and (3) a tailored emergy-based regional ecosystem health index. This establishes a comprehensive suite of indicators for assessing water conservancy projects impacts. Applied to a typical rapidly urbanizing region in China (Langfang City, Hebei Province, 2000–2020), the framework empirically quantified the evolution and health of the regional water-eco-economic system. Results indicate a significant increase in project-related ecological service emergy. The regional water ecosystem health index revealed that the system’s overall health is strongly coupled with socioeconomic pressure, with the ecological-environmental efficiency ratio (rEE/I) emerging as a key indicator reflecting the environmental load and sustainability challenges of rapid development. Significant spatial heterogeneity in emergy composition across land uses was observed, with developed land types exhibiting high economic but low ecological function emergy, highlighting critical spatial planning needs indicated by emergy distribution. Our Emergy-based framework and the derived regional health index effectively diagnose regional sustainability and its drivers. The observed resource-environmental constraints in urbanizing areas, as indicated by our methods, are widely applicable. This study provides a robust set of ecological indicators and a scientific basis for local management, offering valuable, transferable models and technical references for global regions facing similar water resource and infrastructure sustainability issues, significantly contributing to global regional ecological health assessment and sustainable development.</dcterms:abstract>
